            "question_text": "Solve the simultaneous equations \\(2x + y - 5 = 0\\) and \\(x^2 + xy - y^2 = 1\\).",
            "solution_text": "From the linear equation, \\(y = 5 - 2x\\).\nSubstituting this into the quadratic equation gives:\n\\(x^2 + x(5 - 2x) - (5 - 2x)^2 = 1\\)\n\\(x^2 + 5x - 2x^2 - (25 - 20x + 4x^2) = 1\\)\n\\(x^2 + 5x - 2x^2 - 25 + 20x - 4x^2 = 1\\)\n\\(-5x^2 + 25x - 26 = 0\\)\n\\(5x^2 - 25x + 26 = 0\\)\nUsing the quadratic formula:\n\\(x = \\frac{-b \\pm \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}\\)\n\\(x = \\frac{25 \\pm \\sqrt{(-25)^2 - 4(5)(26)}}{2(5)}\\)\n\\(x = \\frac{25 \\pm \\sqrt{625 - 520}}{10}\\)\n\\(x = \\frac{25 \\pm \\sqrt{105}}{10}\\)\nWhen \\(x = \\frac{25 + \\sqrt{105}}{10}\\), \\(y = 5 - 2(\\frac{25 + \\sqrt{105}}{10}) = 5 - \\frac{50 + 2\\sqrt{105}}{10} = \\frac{50 - 50 - 2\\sqrt{105}}{10} = \\frac{-2\\sqrt{105}}{10} = \\frac{-\\sqrt{105}}{5}\\)\nWhen \\(x = \\frac{25 - \\sqrt{105}}{10}\\), \\(y = 5 - 2(\\frac{25 - \\sqrt{105}}{10}) = 5 - \\frac{50 - 2\\sqrt{105}}{10} = \\frac{50 - 50 + 2\\sqrt{105}}{10} = \\frac{2\\sqrt{105}}{10} = \\frac{\\sqrt{105}}{5}\\)\nSo the solutions are \\(x = \\frac{25 + \\sqrt{105}}{10}, y = \\frac{-\\sqrt{105}}{5}\\) and \\(x = \\frac{25 - \\sqrt{105}}{10}, y = \\frac{\\sqrt{105}}{5}\\)."
